.TH "svlogd" "8" 
.SH NAME
svlogd \- runit\[aq]s service logging daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] [\-tttvL] [\-r \f[I]c\f[R]] [\-R \f[I]xyz\f[R]] [\-l
\f[I]len\f[R]] [\-b \f[I]buflen\f[R]] \f[I]logs\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[I]logs\f[R] consists of one or more arguments, each specifying a
directory.
.PP
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] continuously reads log data from its standard input,
optionally filters log messages, and writes the data to one or more
automatically rotated \f[I]logs\f[R].
.PP
Recent log files can automatically be processed by an arbitrary
processor program when they are rotated, and \f[B]svlogd\f[R] can be
told to alert selected log messages to standard error, and through udp.
.PP
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] runs until it sees end\-of\-file on standard input or
is sent a TERM signal, see below.
.SS LOG DIRECTORY
A log directory \f[I]log\f[R] contains some number of old log files, and
the current log file \f[I]current\f[R].
Old log files have a file name starting with \f[I]\[at]\f[R] followed by
a precise timestamp (see the daemontools\[aq] \f[B]tai64n\f[R] program),
indicating when \f[I]current\f[R] was rotated and renamed to this file.
.PP
A log directory additionally contains the lock file \f[I]lock\f[R],
maybe \f[I]state\f[R] and \f[I]newstate\f[R], and optionally the file
\f[I]config\f[R].
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] creates necessary files if they don\[aq]t exist.
.PP
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] has trouble opening a log directory, it prints a
warning, and ignores this log directory.
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] is unable to open all log directories given at the
command line, it exits with an error.
This can happen on start\-up or after receiving a HUP signal.
.SS LOG FILE ROTATION
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] appends selected log messages to the \f[I]current\f[R]
log file.
If \f[I]current\f[R] has \f[I]size\f[R] bytes or more (or there is a
new\-line within the last \f[I]len\f[R] of \f[I]size\f[R] bytes), or is
older than a specified amount of \f[I]time\f[R], \f[I]current\f[R] is
rotated:
.PP
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] closes \f[I]current\f[R], changes permission of
\f[I]current\f[R] to 0755, renames \f[I]current\f[R] to
\[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].s, and starts with a new empty
\f[I]current\f[R].
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] sees \f[I]num\f[R] or more old log files in the log
directory, it removes the oldest one.
Note that this doesn\[aq]t decrease the number of log files if there are
already more than \f[I]num\f[R] log files, this must be done manually,
e.g.\ for keeping 10 log files:
.PP
\f[CR]ls \-1 \[rs]\[at]* |sort |sed \-ne \[aq]10,$p\[aq] |xargs rm\f[R]
.SS PROCESSOR
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] is told to process recent log files, it saves
\f[I]current\f[R] to \[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].u, feeds
\[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].u through \[lq]sh \-c
\[aq]\f[I]processor\f[R]\[aq]\[rq] and writes the output to
\[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].t.
If the \f[I]processor\f[R] finishes successfully,
\[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].t is renamed to \[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].s, and
\[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].u is deleted; otherwise
\[at]\f[I]timestamp\f[R].t is deleted and the \f[I]processor\f[R] is
started again.
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] also saves any output that the \f[I]processor\f[R]
writes to file descriptor 5, and makes that output available on file
descriptor 4 when running \f[I]processor\f[R] on the next log file
rotation.
.PP
A \f[I]processor\f[R] is run in the background.
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] sees a previously started \f[I]processor\f[R] still
running when trying to start a new one for the same \f[I]log\f[R], it
blocks until the currently running \f[I]processor\f[R] has finished
successfully.
Only the HUP signal works in that situation.
Note that this may block any program feeding its log data to
\f[B]svlogd.\f[R]
.SS CONFIG
On startup, and after receiving a HUP signal, \f[B]svlogd\f[R] checks
for each log directory \f[I]log\f[R] if the configuration file
\f[I]log/config\f[R] exists, and if so, reads the file line by line and
adjusts configuration for \f[I]log\f[R] as follows:
.PP
If the line is empty, or starts with a \[lq]#\[rq], it is ignored.
A line of the form
.TP
s\f[I]size\f[R]
sets the maximum file size of \f[I]current\f[R] when \f[B]svlogd\f[R]
should rotate the current log file to \f[I]size\f[R] bytes.
Default is 1000000.
If \f[I]size\f[R] is zero, \f[B]svlogd\f[R] doesn\[aq]t rotate log
files.
You should set \f[I]size\f[R] to at least (2 * \f[I]len\f[R]).
.TP
n\f[I]num\f[R]
sets the number of old log files \f[B]svlogd\f[R] should maintain to
\f[I]num\f[R].
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] sees more that \f[I]num\f[R] old log files in
\f[I]log\f[R] after log file rotation, it deletes the oldest one.
Default is 10.
If \f[I]num\f[R] is zero, \f[B]svlogd\f[R] doesn\[aq]t remove old log
files.
.TP
N\f[I]min\f[R]
sets the minimum number of old log files \f[B]svlogd\f[R] should
maintain to \f[I]min\f[R].
\f[I]min\f[R] must be less than \f[I]num\f[R].
If \f[I]min\f[R] is set, and \f[B]svlogd\f[R] cannot write to
\f[I]current\f[R] because the filesystem is full, and it sees more than
\f[I]min\f[R] old log files, it deletes the oldest one.
.TP
t\f[I]timeout\f[R]
sets the maximum age of the \f[I]current\f[R] log file when
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] should rotate the current log file to \f[I]timeout\f[R]
seconds.
If \f[I]current\f[R] is \f[I]timeout\f[R] seconds old, and is not empty,
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] forces log file rotation.
.TP
!\f[I]processor\f[R]
tells \f[B]svlogd\f[R] to feed each recent log file through
\f[I]processor\f[R] (see above) on log file rotation.
By default log files are not processed.
.TP
u\f[I]a.b.c.d[:port]\f[R]
tells \f[B]svlogd\f[R] to transmit the first \f[I]len\f[R] characters of
selected log messages to the IP address \f[I]a.b.c.d\f[R], port number
\f[I]port\f[R].
If \f[I]port\f[R] isn\[aq]t set, the default port for syslog is used
(514).
\f[I]len\f[R] can be set through the \-l option, see below.
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] has trouble sending udp packets, it writes error
messages to the log directory.
Attention: logging through udp is unreliable, and should be used in
private networks only.
.TP
U\f[I]a.b.c.d[:port]\f[R]
is the same as the \f[I]u\f[R] line above, but the log messages are no
longer written to the log directory, but transmitted through udp only.
Error messages from \f[B]svlogd\f[R] concerning sending udp packages
still go to the log directory.
.TP
p\f[I]prefix\f[R]
tells \f[B]svlogd\f[R] to prefix each line to be written to the log
directory, to standard error, or through UDP, with \f[I]prefix\f[R].
.PP
If a line starts with a \f[I]\-\f[R], \f[I]+\f[R], \f[I]e\f[R], or
\f[I]E\f[R], \f[B]svlogd\f[R] matches the first \f[I]len\f[R] characters
of each log message against \f[I]pattern\f[R] and acts accordingly:
.TP
\-\f[I]pattern\f[R]
the log message is deselected.
.TP
+\f[I]pattern\f[R]
the log message is selected.
.TP
e\f[I]pattern\f[R]
the log message is selected to be printed to standard error.
.TP
E\f[I]pattern\f[R]
the log message is deselected to be printed to standard error.
.PP
Initially each line is selected to be written to \f[I]log/current\f[R].
Deselected log messages are discarded from \f[I]log\f[R].
Initially each line is deselected to be written to standard err.
Log messages selected for standard error are written to standard error.
.SH PATTERN MATCHING
\f[B]svlogd\f[R] matches a log message against the string
\f[I]pattern\f[R] as follows:
.PP
\f[I]pattern\f[R] is applied to the log message one character by one,
starting with the first.
A character not a star (\[lq]*\[rq]) and not a plus (\[lq]+\[rq])
matches itself.
A plus matches the next character in \f[I]pattern\f[R] in the log
message one or more times.
A star before the end of \f[I]pattern\f[R] matches any string in the log
message that does not include the next character in \f[I]pattern\f[R].
A star at the end of \f[I]pattern\f[R] matches any string.
.PP
Timestamps optionally added by \f[B]svlogd\f[R] are not considered part
of the log message.
.PP
An \f[B]svlogd\f[R] pattern is not a regular expression.
For example consider a log message like this
.PP
\f[CR]2005\-12\-18_09:13:50.97618 tcpsvd: info: pid 1977 from 10.4.1.14\f[R]
.PP
The following pattern doesn\[aq]t match
.PP
\f[CR]\-*pid*\f[R]
.PP
because the first star matches up to the first p in tcpsvd, and then the
match fails because i is not s.
To match this log message, you can use a pattern like this instead
.PP
\f[CR]\-*: *: pid *\f[R]
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-t\f[R]
timestamp.
Prefix each selected line with a precise timestamp (see the
daemontools\[aq] \f[B]tai64n\f[R] program) when writing to \f[I]log\f[R]
or to standard error.
.TP
\f[B]\-tt\f[R]
timestamp.
Prefix each selected line with a human readable, sortable UTC timestamp
of the form YYYY\-MM\-DD_HH:MM:SS.xxxxx when writing to \f[I]log\f[R] or
to standard error.
.TP
\f[B]\-ttt\f[R]
timestamp.
Prefix each selected line with a human readable, sortable UTC timestamp
of the form YYYY\-MM\-DDTHH:MM:SS.xxxxx when writing to \f[I]log\f[R] or
to standard error.
.TP
\f[B]\-r\f[R] \f[I]c\f[R]
replace.
\f[I]c\f[R] must be a single character.
Replace non\-printable characters in log messages with \f[I]c\f[R].
Characters are replaced before pattern matching is applied.
.TP
\f[B]\-R\f[R] \f[I]xyz\f[R]
replace charset.
Additionally to non\-printable characters, replace all characters found
in \f[I]xyz\f[R] with \f[I]c\f[R] (default \[lq]_\[rq]).
.TP
\f[B]\-l\f[R] \f[I]len\f[R]
line length.
Pattern matching applies to the first \f[I]len\f[R] characters of a log
message only.
Default is 1000.
.TP
\f[B]\-b\f[R] \f[I]buflen\f[R]
buffer size.
Set the size of the buffer \f[B]svlogd\f[R] uses when reading from
standard input and writing to \f[I]logs\f[R] to \f[I]buflen\f[R].
Default is 1024.
\f[I]buflen\f[R] must be greater than \f[I]len\f[R].
For \f[B]svlogd\f[R] instances that process a lot of data in short time,
the buffer size should be increased to improve performance.
.TP
\f[B]\-L\f[R]
lossy.
If \f[I]current\f[R] can not be written due to \f[I]ENOSPC\f[R] and
other remedies have failed, discard log lines.
If the option is given twice, \f[B]svlogd\f[R] prints a warning to
standard error whenever log data is lost.
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
verbose.
Print verbose messages to standard error.
.SH SIGNALS
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] is sent a HUP signal, it closes and reopens all
\f[I]logs\f[R], and updates their configuration according to
\f[I]log/config\f[R].
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] has trouble opening a log directory, it prints a
warning, and discards this log directory.
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] is unable to open all log directories given at the
command line, it exits with an error.
.PP
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] is sent a TERM signal, or if it sees end\-of\-file
on standard input, it stops reading standard input, processes the data
in the buffer, waits for all \f[I]processor\f[R] subprocesses to finish
if any, and exits 0 as soon as possible.
.PP
If \f[B]svlogd\f[R] is sent an ALRM signal, it forces log file rotation
for all \f[I]logs\f[R] with a non empty \f[I]current\f[R] log file.
